04825nam a22005415i 9780774850100DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072001xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748501007 a10.59962/97807748501002doi  a(DE-B1597)661694  a(OCoLC)743412275  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1089.O5bP37 2001eb 7aHIS0060202bisacsh04a971.1/503/09200aHobnobbing with a Countess and Other Okanagan Adventures :bThe Diaries of Alice Barrett Parke, 1891-1900 /ced. by Jo Fraser Jones. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b39 b&w photographs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Pioneers of British Columbia00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tQuite away from all my people -- tThe real, the useful, the necessary–these occupy one here -- tA very cosy, happy home -- tHow many people I have got to know! -- tOh! I do hope I’ll be able to do something useful and good -- tA great many people have ailments here -- tHow I love them all -- tOh! I wish I could hear someone who would stir me up -- tA man of Mr. Parke’s ability -- tI have been as busy as I could be -- tThere is much of the untamed animal nature in me -- tThe women work much harder than the men -- tHob-nobbing with a Countess -- tI think if I were a man I’d want to go in for [politics] -- tPeople really seem to be getting sanguine over the mining prospects around here -- tIt really is shameful the way I neglect my poor old diary lately -- tI wonder when I’m a grey haired old woman if I will enjoy reading these papers! -- tNotes -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tAppendix C -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1891, Alice Barrett moved from Port Dover, Ontario, to the Okanagan Valley to keep house for her brother and uncle. She soon married Harold Parke, a former NWMP officer, and spent the next decade recording her experiences in a series of notebooks sent to her Ontario family. Few women's diaries have survived from that time, and Barrett Parke recalls a period of profound transformation in a region newly opened to white settlement by the railway. She was an astute observer and an exceptional writer, and her diaries provide invaluable insights into work, health, religion, race and gender relations, and women's lives. On a personal level, her writings show the conflict between her independent spirit and women's traditional roles. Although wary of the emerging feminism of the time, Alice was co-opted into the "vice-regal circle" of the Countess of Aberdeen, who stayed at nearby Coldstream Ranch, and became the first corresponding secretary of the Vernon chapter of the National Council of Women. Careful editing and additional research to contextualize the social and historical background, as well as biographical details, photos, and maps enhance the reader's understanding and appreciation of this remarkable woman's life, and the lives of those around her. Selected as a BC Book for Everybody.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aJones, Jo Fraser, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485010040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850100423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter